CETME .308

- Tri Rail Handguard

- UTG Rail Covers
- Hogue Slip On Grip.

The original handguard is also included in case you prefer the classic Spanish CETME/FAL/G3 look or don't need the added bulk of the rail.

I've taken this gun out a few times, less than 500 rounds through it. There's very minimal surface rust in some small crevice areas near the sling mount, and the rear sight is missing the aperture, spring, pin, and ball bearing - this can be purchased for a total of $21 at https://www.buymilsurp.com/rifle-parts-accessories-cetme-rifle-parts-accessories-c-3548_368.html?page=2&sort=20a. It's a simple installation, I just lost mine after a recent disassembly and don't want to deal with it. I've knocked $40 off my intended price to cover your time and expense.

Beyond that, this rifle is in great condition and you'll be getting 80 rounds of Brown Bear .308 and 60 rounds of Silver Bear 140 Grain SP as well.

Priced below many comparable semi-auto .308's, this is a solid "battle rifle" package. The weight of the rifle helps keep the .308 recoil manageable. Even out of the 16" barrel, the .308 round still provides a great advantage over 5.56/.223 in many ways. The flash hider works well, and you'll find it's relatively easy stay on target with your follow up shots.

If you're on the fence about getting a larger caliber than the average semi-auto rifle, this is a very manageable .308 for well below the currently inflated price of an AR-15 and you'll have plenty left for ammo and range time.

title: For Sale:  WWI USGI 1911 Parts for Sale!
postcontent:
Please read entire listing.

I have decided to let go of my 1911 parts, which are a collection that was amassed over decades of collecting.  These are rare parts, and if you have a WWI 1911 that has incorrect parts on it, the value is hurt significantly.  

So, the investment of a couple hundred dollars to make yours correct, could increase the value by 4x or 5x that amount, or more.  When knowing collectors look at a 1911, they scrutinize every part, and expect it to be right.

Here is all I have, and the prices (the number corresponds with the tag in the photo - due to Armslist size restrictions, there is a Photobucket link below to copy / paste in your browser):

18: Two-tone "R" stamped (Risdon Mfg Co.) magazine = $125
19: Two-tone "R" stamped (Risdon Mfg Co.) magazine = $100
20: Two-tone "R" stamped (Risdon Mfg Co.) magazine = $100
56: Wooden 'Double Diamond' grips (pair) = $275
54: Wooden 28-row Checkered grips (pair) = $300
55: Wooden 'Double Diamond' grips (pair) = $300
57: Wooden 28-row Checkered grip (single / rt panel only) = $50
10: Vertical "H P" barrel = $300
9: Intertwined "H P" barrel = $300
31: Long Trigger = $100
32: Long Trigger = $125
44: Checkered slide stop = $110
45: Checkered slide stop = $110
46: Checkered slide stop = $110
36: Flat mainspring housing = $100
48: Long wide-spur hammer with bordered checkering = $110
49: Long wide-spur hammer with no border on checkering = $110
50: Long wide-spur hammer checkered to edge, no border = $110
27: Short-tang grip safety = $70
1: Slide, has early U-notch rear sight, narrow front sight, and "M1911 A1 US ARMY" on right side - complete with firing pin, extractor, and firing-pin stop = $400

If you are serious about buying, please e-mail me what you are interested in.

I will only take a USPS or Western Union money order - no PayPal, for reasons of philosophy.

As it relates to my prices, I have put them under what eBay auctions are closing at for like parts, and what I'm seeing at shows.  

I beg you, please do not send me an e-mail complaining about where I've set my prices.  I am not forcing anyone to buy them, and if you are a serious collector, you know what they're worth.  Look at what correct WWI barrels are selling for on eBay ($400+).  Grips are astronomical in price, but again, if you have an otherwise correct WWI USGI 1911, and it has after-market grips on it, it really hurts value.

If you buy multiple parts, I may work with you on price a LITTLE, but I am not going to give them away.  These are getting harder and harder to find, and are only going up in price.  We're coming up on the 100th anniversary of WWI, which is going to cause a spike in prices as well.

I will consider trades, but nothing modern.  Would need to be militaria (helmets, firearms, inert ordnance, etc) from WWI or WWII, any country.

All photos here:  s1173.beta.photobucket.com/user/gi1911/library/WWI%20Parts (you will have to manually type the "http://" in front of it)

Thank you.

title: For Sale:  1948 Lee-Enfield .303 Ishapore
postcontent:
Up for sale is a beautiful 1948 No. 1 Mk. 3* (not Mk. III*) manufactured by India's Ishapore factory. Details below: 

* The rifle is in overall excellent condition. Nose cap, sights, barrel, receiver, and magazine all match. While the bolt does NOT match, this is very common for Indian rifles, often stripped of the bolt before being stored. 

* The nosecap is correct; aside from having matching numbers, the stacking swivel lug remains undrilled, as all Ishapores were. 

* Original 2000m sights, numbers-matching.

* Ishapore screw is present, this isn't one of the later hex bolts. 

* The buttstock bears the "TDE" stamp that signifies post-Independence manufacture. 

* The bore of this rifle is, simply put, fucking gorgeous. Seriously. I put 50 rounds of Partizan through it after acquiring the rifle a while back, and it's been cleaned and oiled ever since. The lands and grooves are razor sharp, almost brand new. 

* Brass buttplate and the buttstock show signs of regular use, very nice condition. The wooden furniture is in excellent condition overall; the only damage is a little bit of missing wood on the upper rear hand guard, like somebody tried to pry it up too aggressively and chipped a small bit off. 

* The stampings on the action's wrist really mark the rifle as special: They read "GRI 1948 No. 1 Mk. 3*". Prior to August 15, 1947 India was still a British colony; as such all rifles would be stamped GRI for "Georgius Rex, Imperator". Post August 15, 1947 rifles should be stamped RFI for "Rifle Factory, Ishapore". As such, this is what's known as a "transition rifle" due to it's being manufactured post-Independence on British tooling, by workers that were British-trained. This isn't a sloppy 60's .308, it's just as good as a BSA or Lithgow made during the Interwar years. 

* Chambered in .303. 

This is an awesome rifle that's in amazing shape and has a great history. It's all-original save for the bolt, but aside from not being numbers-matching the bolt is a proper Indian example. I'm selling to generate money for a nice Enfield .22 trainer that I've got a line on. 

I have more pictures available upon request. 

$525 is pretty firm. I might be willing to consider negotiating or trades a bit if the buyer's serious. Face-to-face meetings preferred: I will ship the rifle to an FFL, but The buyer pays shipping and transfer fees, tacked onto the final cost. 

Thanks for looking! Please reply to this listing or text me at (330)_727_2675 for more info.

title: For Sale:  NIB (old) 1932 Hex Receiver Tula Mosin Nagant 91/30
postcontent: Few rifles seem to attract as much attention at the range as a Mosin Nagant.  I can be alternating between my Finnish Mosin and my Remington 700 PSS in 300 win mag, and people always ask about the Mosin.    They are fun to shoot and the ammo is highly available.  I have a 1932 Tula Mosin Nagant 91/30 rifle with the hex receiver for sale, it has a bayonet, sling, leather ammo patch, cleaning kit and oil can.  This is not a dubious late war Izevhsk, but a solid rifle.  It is one of the better Mosin Nagants, next to the Finnish Mosins with FN barrels (which I already own and love.)  This is a nice Mosin, with matching numbers and it will shoot well as is, the trigger is pretty good.  I would clean up the trigger a bit for a great trigger break ( or you could drop a Timney trigger in, but it really doesn't need that, unless that is what you like.) .  If you wanted, bedding it in a new composite thumbhole stock, isn't a bad option considering the overall barrel, receiver and trigger quality.  The magazine floor plate was armory re-numbered, but that is common.  There is still Cosmoline on the gun and I have never fired this.  I should probably keep this gun, but I need to make room in the safe as I have been re-arranging my collection.

I will only take a USPS or Western Union money order - no PayPal, for reasons of philosophy.

As it relates to my prices, I have put them under what eBay auctions are closing at for like parts, and what I'm seeing at shows.

I beg you, please do not send me an e-mail complaining about where I've set my prices. I am not forcing anyone to buy them, and if you are a serious collector, you know what they're worth. Look at what correct WWI barrels are selling for on eBay ($400+). Grips are astronomical in price, but again, if you have an otherwise correct WWI USGI 1911, and it has after-market grips on it, it really hurts value.

If you buy multiple parts, I may work with you on price a LITTLE, but I am not going to give them away. These are getting harder and harder to find, and are only going up in price. We're coming up on the 100th anniversary of WWI, which is going to cause a spike in prices as well.

I will consider trades, but nothing modern. Would need to be militaria (helmets, firearms, inert ordnance, etc) from WWI or WWII, any country.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning 12 Ga. Double Auto Twentyweight
location: Surfside Beach, Myrtle Beach, South Carolina
postcontent:
The Browning Double Automatic Shotgun is a short recoil operated  semi-automatic (Auto Loading) 12 gauge 2-3/4 chamber shotgun. This shotgun was offered in both aluminum and steel receiver configurations with the aluminum receivers featuring a variety of finish colors.The 3 versions offered include the Standard as the only steel receiver version, Twelvette, and Twentyweight which used the aluminium receiver. All Double Automatic's are 12 gauge. Various configurations were available for choke, barrel length, and barrel type. The firearm was produced between 1955 and 1971, with production volume of approximately 67,000.

This firearm features a unique loading port on the left side of the receiver.As the first round is loaded, the shell is lifted by a mechanism and chambered by the bolt; once the bolt is closed, the lifting mechanism returns to the resting position below the loading port, where the next round can then be loaded. Upon firing the chambered round, the shell in the loading port is automatically chambered. The total capacity is 2 with 1 chambered round and 1 in the loading port.
US Patent #2,586,509 issued to Val Browning Feb 19, 1952

I hear these are somewhat hard to find, this gun is the Twentyweight, with the Brown  trigger gaurd, all gold work is still beautiful, stamped A32 and has a 3 digit number. Has modified choke and 26 inch barrel
